    {
      "id": "executive-summary",
      "title": "Executive Summary",
      "intent": "executive-summary",
      "content": "- U.S. electricity demand growth has re-accelerated, with data centers now a core structural driver rather than a cyclical tailwind.\n- DOE/LBNL estimate data center load rose from 58 TWh (2014) to 176 TWh (2023), with a 2028 range of 325-580 TWh.\n- Data centers represented ~4.4% of U.S. electricity in 2023 and are projected at ~6.7-12% by 2028.\n- EIA projects U.S. electricity use growth of 1% in 2026 and 3% in 2027, the strongest 4-year run since 2000.\n- IEA estimates U.S. data center demand around 180 TWh in 2024 and ~+240 TWh by 2030 vs. 2024 levels.\n- Grid operators are revising long-term peaks upward; PJM now models materially higher summer and winter peaks over 20 years.\n- Winning playbooks combine faster interconnection governance, flexible load design, and generation/transmission sequencing.\n- Near-term bottlenecks are less about annual energy and more about coincident peak, queue uncertainty, and local deliverability.\n- Leadership teams need a portfolio view: demand quality, locational strategy, and pace-layered supply contracts.",
      "layout_slug": "recommendations-white",
      "variant": "white",
      "expected_slides": 1,
      "status": "draft",
      "sources": [
        {
          "label": "https://www.energy.gov/articles/doe-releases-new-report-evaluating-increase-electricity-demand-data-centers",
