    {
      "id": "regional-reliability-stress-pjm-case",
      "title": "Regional Reliability Stress: PJM Case",
      "intent": "risks",
      "content": "- Risk: Summer peak grows to >241 GW over 15 years, outrunning historical planning assumptions.\n- Risk: Winter peak gap narrows, reducing seasonal flexibility in reserve planning.\n- Risk: Large-load timing uncertainty complicates transmission and capacity procurement.\n- Risk: Local congestion and deliverability constraints increase curtailment/cost risk.\n- Mitigation: Stage data center energization gates to verified network readiness milestones.\n- Mitigation: Procure flexible demand operations (onsite backup/storage/demand response) for peak events.\n- Mitigation: Use dual-path supply strategy (firm + renewable + balancing) with explicit locational screens.\n- Mitigation: Build utility/operator planning cells that continuously re-forecast load realization.",
      "layout_slug": "risks-mitigations",
      "variant": "white",
      "expected_slides": 1,
      "status": "draft",
      "sources": [
        {
          "label": "https://insidelines.pjm.com/pjms-updated-20-year-forecast-continues-to-see-significant-long-term-load-growth/",
          "url": "https://insidelines.pjm.com/pjms-updated-20-year-forecast-continues-to-see-significant-long-term-load-growth/"
        }
      ],
      "created_at": "2026-02-06T18:05:06+00:00",
      "updated_at": "2026-02-06T18:05:06+00:00",
      "order": 40
    },
    {
      "id": "supply-stack-implications",
      "title": "Supply Stack Implications",
      "intent": "comparison",
      "content": "- Renewables: fast deployment, strong corporate procurement fit, but intermittency requires balancing tools.\n- Natural gas: dispatchable bridge for reliability; fuel and permitting risk require portfolio hedging.\n- Nuclear/geothermal: strategic long-term firming options, slower commercialization cycles.\n- Storage: critical for intraday balancing and peak shaving, less effective for prolonged deficits alone.\n- Left side (Speed): renewables + targeted gas + storage provide near-term capacity velocity.\n- Right side (Durability): transmission + firm low-carbon assets anchor long-horizon reliability economics.",
      "layout_slug": "two-column-comparison",
      "variant": "white",
      "expected_slides": 1,
      "status": "draft",
      "sources": [
        {
          "label": "https://www.iea.org/reports/energy-and-ai/energy-demand-from-ai",
          "url": "https://www.iea.org/reports/energy-and-ai/energy-demand-from-ai"
        },
        {
          "label": "https://www.energy.gov/articles/doe-releases-new-report-evaluating-increase-electricity-demand-data-centers",
          "url": "https://www.energy.gov/articles/doe-releases-new-report-evaluating-increase-electricity-demand-data-centers"
        }
      ],
      "created_at": "2026-02-06T18:05:06+00:00",
      "updated_at": "2026-02-06T18:05:06+00:00",
      "order": 50
    },
    {
      "id": "12-month-utility-scale-action-plan",
      "title": "12-Month Utility-Scale Action Plan",
      "intent": "implementation",
      "content": "- Month 0-2: Build large-load registry, confidence-score pipeline projects, and align planning assumptions with operators.\n- Month 2-4: Segment projects by energization criticality and locational grid risk.\n- Month 4-6: Contract flexible load packages and initiate transmission-ready design reviews.\n- Month 6-9: Lock medium-term supply portfolio and trigger phased interconnection governance checkpoints.\n- Month 9-12: Run reliability drills (summer/winter stress) and re-baseline queue realization probabilities.\n- KPI 1: % of load with validated network deliverability.\n- KPI 2: MW of flexible load under executable control.\n- KPI 3: Variance between forecast and realized energization dates.",
      "layout_slug": "timeline-milestones",
      "variant": "white",
      "expected_slides": 1,
      "status": "draft",
